1. Intro¶



In this project, we will use the MNIST handwritten digits dataset from http://yann.lecun.com/exdb/mnist/ to dive into machine learning. We will be implementing three differenct types of classifiers: K-Nearest Neighbors, Neural Nets and Convolutional Neural Nets on the dataset and compare the three classifiers.

2. Data preparation¶



"The MNIST database of handwritten digits, available from this page, has a training set of 60,000 examples, and a test set of 10,000 examples. It is a subset of a larger set available from NIST. The digits have been size-normalized and centered in a fixed-size image." MNIST

The data was read into datasets by read function (Code taken from https://gist.github.com/akesling/5358964 )

In [1]:
import os
import struct
import numpy as np

# Change path as required
path = "./mnist"

def read(dataset="training", datatype='images'):
    """
    Python function for importing the MNIST data set.  It returns an iterator
    of 2-tuples with the first element being the label and the second element
    being a numpy.uint8 2D array of pixel data for the given image.
    """

    if dataset is "training":
        fname_img = os.path.join(path, 'train-images.idx3-ubyte')
        fname_lbl = os.path.join(path, 'train-labels.idx1-ubyte')
    elif dataset is "testing":
        fname_img = os.path.join(path, 't10k-images.idx3-ubyte')
        fname_lbl = os.path.join(path, 't10k-labels.idx1-ubyte')

    # Load everything in some numpy arrays
    with open(fname_lbl, 'rb') as flbl:
        magic, num = struct.unpack(">II", flbl.read(8))
        lbl = np.fromfile(flbl, dtype=np.int8)

    with open(fname_img, 'rb') as fimg:
        magic, num, rows, cols = struct.unpack(">IIII", fimg.read(16))
        img = np.fromfile(fimg, dtype=np.uint8).reshape(len(lbl), rows, cols)
    
    if(datatype=='images'):
        get_data = lambda idx: img[idx]
    elif(datatype=='labels'):
        get_data = lambda idx: lbl[idx]

    # Create an iterator which returns each image in turn
    for i in range(len(lbl)):
        yield get_data(i)

3. Helper functions: TODO test->Test¶



  • DataBatch: to help split dataset into batches,return data/label indices in batches

  • test: return test accuracy for classifiers (50 samples per batch)

  • Confusion: return accuracy as well as the confusion matrix

    • The matrix (M) should be nxn where n is the number of classes. Entry M[i,j] should contain the fraction of images of class i that were classified as class j.

  • VisualizeConfusion: plot the Confusion Matrix

In [4]:
# Using the tqdm module to visualize run time is suggested
from tqdm import tqdm
import time

# a generator for batches of data
# yields data (batchsize, 3, 32, 32) and labels (batchsize)
# if shuffle, it will load batches in a random order
def DataBatch(data, label, batchsize, shuffle=True):
    n = data.shape[0]
    if shuffle:
        index = np.random.permutation(n)
    else:
        index = np.arange(n)
    for i in range(int(np.ceil(n/batchsize))):
        inds = index[i*batchsize : min(n,(i+1)*batchsize)]
        yield data[inds], label[inds]

# tests the accuracy of a classifier
def test(testData, testLabels, classifier):
    batchsize=50
    correct=0.
    for data,label in DataBatch(testData,testLabels,batchsize,shuffle=False):
        prediction = classifier(data)
        correct += np.sum(prediction==label)
    return correct/testData.shape[0]


# It would be a good idea to return the accuracy, along with the confusion 
# matrix, since both can be calculated in one iteration over test data, to 
# save time
def Confusion(testData, testLabels, classifier):
    M = np.zeros((10,10))
    accuracy=0.
    correct=0.
    #let col keep track of predictions and rows keep track of actual instances
    for data, label in tqdm( DataBatch(testData,testLabels,200,shuffle=False) ):
        prediction = classifier(data)
        for i,j in zip(label,prediction):
            M[i,j] += 1
        correct += np.sum(prediction==label)
    
    #normalize each row of the matrix
    for i in range(10):
        M[i,:]=np.divide(M[i,:],np.sum(M[i,:]))
        M = np.round(M,4)
        
    accuracy= correct/testData.shape[0]
    return M, accuracy

def VisualizeConfusion(M):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    plt.imshow(M)
    for (x, y), value in np.ndenumerate(M):
        plt.text(y, x, f"{value:.2%}", va="center", ha="center",color="orange")
    
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
    plt.ylabel('True Label')
    plt.colorbar()



4. Random Classifier¶



First of all, we want to know if we are purely guessing randomly, what will the accuracy be. By common sense, we are guessing from 10 digits randomly when only 1 digit is the correct answer. We expect the accuracy to be around 10%

# a sample classifier
# given an input it outputs a random class
class RandomClassifier():
    def __init__(self, classes=10):
        self.classes=classes
    def __call__(self, x):
        return np.random.randint(self.classes, size=x.shape[0])

5. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)¶



In k-NN classification, the output is a class membership. An object is classified by a plurality vote of its neighbors, with the object being assigned to the class most common among its k nearest neighbors (k is a positive integer, typically small). If k = 1, then the object is simply assigned to the class of that single nearest neighbor. (Wiki)

Here we implement a simple knn classifier using sklearn's KNeighborsClassifier. The distance metric is Euclidean in pixel space, and k, the number of neighbors involved in voting, is set to be 3.

In [7]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import plot_confusion_matrix
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
class KNNClassifier():
    def __init__(self, k=3):
        # k is the number of neighbors involved in voting
        self.classifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)        

    def train(self, trainData, trainLabels):
        n,H,W = trainData.shape
        tD=np.reshape(trainData,(n,H*W))
        self.classifier.fit(tD,trainLabels)
        
    def __call__(self, x):
        # this method should take a batch of images
        # and return a batch of predictions
        n,H,W = x.shape
        tD=np.reshape(x,(n,H*W))
        return self.classifier.predict(tD)

Comment:¶

  • The accuracy for our KNN classifier trained on the entire training dataset is approximately 97%

  • According to our confusion matrix, we have some discoveries:

    • Number 8 are the most difficult to recognized. Numbers 0,1 are the most easy to be recognized.

    • Number 1 is most likely to be misclassified 2.

    • Number 2 is most likely to be misclassified as 7 and vice versa.

    • Number 3 is most likely to be misclassified as 5.and vice versa

    • Number 4 is most likely to be misclassified as 1 and 9.

    • Number 6 is most likely to be misclassified as 1.

    • Number 8 is most likely to be misclassified as 3 and 5.

    • Number 9 is most likely to be misclassified as 3 and 7.

6. Neural Nets¶

We will be using PyTorch and it's nn module to set a framework for our neural network.

The nn package defines a set of Modules, which are roughly equivalent to neural network layers. A Module receives input Tensors and computes output Tensors, but may also hold internal state such as Tensors containing learnable parameters.(PyTorch)


6.1 Helper functions¶

We defined class PTClassifier as our custom classifier container class. The train function for PTClassifier will be used with different networks later on in this project.

In [9]:
# base class for PyTorch networks. The full training loop includes
# (__init__), (train) and prediction(__call__) 
from __future__ import print_function
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
from torch.nn.parameter import Parameter
import torch.nn.functional as F
import torch.nn.init
import torch.optim as optim
from torch.autograd import Variable
from tqdm import tqdm
from scipy.stats import truncnorm

class PTClassifier():
    def __init__(self, net):
        self.net = net()
    
    def train(self, trainData, trainLabels, testData, testLabels, epochs=1, batchsize=50):
        criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss() #loss function
        learning_rate=3e-4
        optimizer = optim.Adam(self.net.parameters(),lr=learning_rate) #Optimizer keep and update weights/bias
        
        for epoch in range(epochs):
            
            #train models in 50 batches
            for i, (data,label) in enumerate(DataBatch(trainData, trainLabels, batchsize, shuffle=True)):
                inputs = Variable(torch.FloatTensor(data))
                targets = Variable(torch.LongTensor(label))

                # Train the model using the optimizer and the batch data  
                optimizer.zero_grad()   # zero the gradient buffers
                output = self.net(inputs)    #get output
                loss = criterion(output, targets) #calculate loss gradient w.r.t output
                loss.backward()    #back propogate to get loss gradient w.r.t input
                optimizer.step()     #update weights and bias
                
            print ('Epoch:{:d} Accuracy: {:.2%}'.format(epoch+1, test(testData, testLabels, self)))
    
    #predict(x)
    def __call__(self, x):
        inputs = Variable(torch.FloatTensor(x))
        prediction = self.net(inputs)
        return np.argmax(prediction.data.cpu().numpy(), 1)
    
    def get_first_layer_weights(self):
        return self.net.weight1.data.cpu().numpy()

# helper function to get weight variable
def weight_variable(shape):
    initial = torch.Tensor(truncnorm.rvs(-1/0.01, 1/0.01, scale=0.01, size=shape))
    return Parameter(initial, requires_grad=True)

# helper function to get bias variable
def bias_variable(shape):
    initial = torch.Tensor(np.ones(shape)*0.1)
    return Parameter(initial, requires_grad=True)

6.2 Single Layer Perceptron¶

We implemented single layer perceptron and test its performance

In [10]:
# Define Single Layer Perceptron network
class SLP(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, in_features=28*28, classes=10):
        super(SLP, self).__init__()
        # model variables
        self.weight1 = weight_variable((classes, in_features))
        self.bias1 = bias_variable((classes))
        
    def forward(self, x):
        # linear operation
        y_pred = torch.addmm(self.bias1, x.view(list(x.size())[0], -1), self.weight1.t())
        return y_pred

6.2 Multi Layer Perceptron¶
The MLP consists of 2 layers of matrix multiplication and bias offset that map to the following feature dimensions:


    

  • 28x28 -> hidden (100)
    • 

  • hidden -> classes (10)
    • 












In [15]:



     


# Define Multi Layer Perceptron network
class MLP(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, in_features=28*28, hidden=100, classes=10):
        super(MLP, self).__init__()
        self.weight1 = weight_variable((hidden, in_features))
        self.bias1 = bias_variable((hidden))
        self.weight2 = weight_variable((classes, hidden))
        self.bias2 = bias_variable((classes))
        
    def forward(self, x):
        hidden = torch.addmm(self.bias1, x.view(list(x.size())[0], -1), self.weight1.t())
        hidden = F.relu(hidden)
        y_pred = torch.addmm(self.bias2, hidden.view(list(hidden.size())[0], -1), self.weight2.t())
        return y_pred

7. Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) [5 pts]¶
Here we are implementing a CNN with the following architecture:


    

  • n=5
    • 

  • ReLU( Conv(kernel_size=4x4, stride=2, output_features=n) )
    • 

  • ReLU( Conv(kernel_size=4x4, stride=2, output_features=n*2) )
    • 

  • ReLU( Conv(kernel_size=4x4, stride=2, output_features=n*4) )
    • 

  • Linear(output_features=classes)
    • 












In [19]:



     


def conv2d(x, W, stride):
    # x: input
    # W: weights (out, in, kH, kW)
    return F.conv2d(x, W, stride=stride, padding=1)

# Define Convolutional Neural Network
class CNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, classes=10, n=5):
        super(CNN, self).__init__()
        self.weight1 = weight_variable((n,1,4,4))
        self.bias1 = bias_variable((n,14,14))    #[(WK+2P)/S]+1.
        
        self.weight2 = weight_variable((n*2,n,4,4))  
        self.bias2 = bias_variable((n*2,7,7))
        
        self.weight3 = weight_variable((n*4,n*2,4,4))   
        self.bias3 = bias_variable((n*4,3,3))
        
        #linear
        self.weight4 = weight_variable((classes,4*n*3*3))
        self.bias4 = bias_variable((classes))
 
    def forward(self, x):
        x = F.relu(conv2d(x,self.weight1,2)+self.bias1)
        x = F.relu(conv2d(x,self.weight2,2)+self.bias2)
        x = F.relu(conv2d(x,self.weight3,2)+self.bias3)

        y_pred = torch.addmm(self.bias4, x.view(list(x.size())[0], -1), self.weight4.t())
        return y_pred

Conclusion¶
In summary, we briefly walked over four different types of classifiers: KNN/SLP/MLP/CNN.  And their corresponding accuracy is around 97%/92%/97%/98%. Note that the MLP/ConvNet approaches lead to an accuracy a little higher than the K-NN approach. In general, neural net approaches lead to a significant increase in accuracy, but in this case the problem is not too hard, so the increase in accuracy will not be very high. The performance of various machine learning methods on this problem is recorded at http://yann.lecun.com/exdb/mnist/
